The paper deals with the problem of topology discovery of sparse random graphs using end-to-end random measurements between a subset of nodes. This problem is related to network topology inference, which is a common topic in the field of computer networks. The paper proposes algorithms for topology discovery under two routing models and analyzes the number of participants required for accurate discovery. This work involves concepts from information theory, networking, and graph theory, which are all relevant to the sub-categories of cs.IT, cs.NI, cs.DS, cs.SI, and cs.SY.
